above).","Catalan: occupational name for a barber, <i>barber</i> (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Barbier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Dominique, Emile, Pierre, Alexandre, Gilles, Jacques, Laurent, Laurette, Manon, Marcel, Marcellin, Michel.","French: occupational name for a barber-surgeon (see   Barber  ), Old French <i>barbier</i> (from Late Latin <i>barbarius</i>, a derivative of <i>barba</i> ‘beard’). Compare   Barbe   and   Barbee  .","German: occupational name for a barber, from Middle High German <i>barbierer</i>, or an occupational name for an armorer, from <i>barbier(e)</i> ‘metal visor (to protect the face)’."]},{"name":"Berber","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Salvador, Guillermo, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Luis, Adriana, Alfredo, Angelina, Armando, Carlos.","Catalan: probably a variant of   Barber  . This surname is most common in Mexico.","Turkish: occupational name from <i>berber</i> ‘barber’."]},{"name":"Barbero","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Ricardo, Alvino, Ana, Angel, Arsenio, Fernando, Gustavo, Jaime, Jose, Maribel, Mario, Nenita.  Italian Aldo, Angelo, Domenic, Ernani, Giulio, Italo.  French Emile, Yves.","Spanish and Italian (Piedmont): occupational name for a barber-surgeon, <i>barbero</i>, from Late Latin <i>barbarius</i>, a derivative of <i>barba</i> ‘beard’ (from Latin <i>barba</i>); see also   Barber  . This surname is also found in southern France."]},{"name":"Barbieri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Salvatore, Angelo, Vito, Rocco, Aldo, Cosmo, Dino, Domenic, Geno, Giovanna, Guido.","Italian: occupational name from <i>barbiere</i> ‘barber-surgeon’ (see   Barber  ), from Late Latin <i>barbarius</i>, a derivative of <i>barba</i> ‘beard’."]},{"name":"Barbour","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: occupational name from Old French <i>barbeor</i> ‘barber’. Compare the English form   Barber  .","History: George Barbour sailed from England on the <i>Transport</i> in 1635. He became a freeman of Dedham, MA, in 1647 and settled eventually at Medfield. A Scottish merchant named Barbour settled in eastern VA in the latter half of the 17th century."]},{"name":"Borbely","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Zoltan, Antal, Ferenc, Ildiko, Kalman, Laszlo, Miklos.","Hungarian (<b>Borbély</b>): occupational name for a barber, Hungarian <i>borbély</i>. See also   Barber  ."]},{"name":"Barbeau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Pierre, Monique, Alcide, Alphonse, Amiee, Armand, Gisele, Jean Francois, Lucien, Lucienne, Michel.","French:","from <i>barbeau</i> ‘barbel’, a type of fish, hence a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, or a nickname for a man with a sparse beard, the fish being distinguished by beardlike growths on either side of its mouth."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Barber Earl of Suffolk was born in 1410, in Fressingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Roger St Barber de Ashington, was 43 and his mother, Margaret Longland, was 40. He married Lady Margery Stanley about 1434, in Fressingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1457, in his hometown, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1410–1457":"1410–1457","1398–1472":"1398–1472","1410–1480":"1410–1480","1434–1489":"1434–1489","1367–1457":"1367–1457","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1457":"1457","1434":"1434","1489":"1489","before 1398":"enne 1398","1367":"1367","1410":"1410","1398":"1398","1472":"1472","Abt 1434":"umbes 1434","1370":"1370","1480":"1480","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Fressingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Fressingfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Fressingfield, Suffolk, England":"F